revision.text:
When the [[Kingdom of Navarre]] was united with France by the marriage of [[Philip IV of France]] with [[Joan I of Navarre|Joan I]] Queen Regnant of [[Kingdom of Navarre|Navarre]] and [[Count of Champagne|Countess of Champagne]] on 16 August 1284, it kept the long existing '''Chancery of Navarre''' ''(French: Chancellerie de Navarre)''. The [[Kings of Navarre]] had private [[Chancellors]] dating back to ancient kings. [[Theobald II of Navarre]] had a Vice-Chancellor, according to letters dated 1259.
In 1512, [[Ferdinand II of Aragon|Ferdinand the Catholic]], [[King of Aragon]] and son of [[John II of Aragon and Navarre]], invaded the [[Kingdom of Navarre]], beginning the [[Spanish conquest of Iberian Navarre]], during the reign of [[John III of Navarre|Jean III d'Albret]] and [[Catherine of Navarre|Catherine de Foix-Béarn]], and quickly conquered all of [[Upper Navarre]] and part of [[Lower Navarre]]. [[John III of Navarre|Jean III d'Albret]] tried to retake his kingdom, first in 1512, but failed despite French support, then again in 1516. Depressed by the defeats and adverse diplomatic results, he died at the castle of Esgouarrabaque in [[Monein]], in [[Béarn]], on 14 June 1516. His son, [[Henry II of Navarre|Henry II]], attempted to reconquer the kingdom, again with French help, but this time supported by a popular revolt, however, despite some initial success, he was defeated at the [[Battle of Noáin]] on 30 June 1521 and lost all he had reconquered.
[[Henry II of Navarre|Henry II]] moved his capital to [[Saint-Palais, Pyrénées-Atlantiques|Saint-Palais]]. In 1524, [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles Quint]] invaded [[Guyenne]] and [[Lower Navarre]]. [[Henry II of Navarre|Henry II]] was taken prisoner during the [[Battle of Pavia]], in French-controlled [[Lombardy]], on 24 February 1525, and married [[Marguerite d'Angoulême]], the sister of [[Francis I of France|François I of France]] the following year. A new attempt by [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles Quint]] to reconquer [[Lower Navarre]] in 1527 was only partially successful, after which he abandoned the idea of reconquering the country.
The deconsecrated St. Paul's Church housed the ''Chancery of Navarre'' for the century of its existence [[Saint-Palais, Pyrénées-Atlantiques|Saint-Palais]], from 1524–1624. The 1522–23 meetings of the Estates of Navarre were also held in the building.
== Chancellors of Navarre: 1512–1624 ==
''Pierre de Biaix'' was already ''Chancellor of Navarre'' in 1512<ref name="La Boulinière (1825), pp. 323–324">La Boulinière (1825), pp. 323–324 [https://books.google.com/books?id=4LI9AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA323 (in French)]</ref> when the kingdom was invaded and remained loyal to [[Henry II of Navarre|Henry II]] following the death of [[John III of Navarre|Jean III d'Albret]]. He remained ''Chancellor of Navarre'' until at least 11 August 1526,<ref name="Bascle de Lagrèze (1851), p. 342">Bascle de Lagrèze (1851), p. 342 [https://books.google.com/books?id=QOtAAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA342 (in French)]</ref> perhaps longer.
The position of ''Chancellor of Navarre'' was eliminated at the time of the formation of the ''Parliament of Navarre and Béarn'' in 1624.<ref>Encyclopédie ou Dictionnaire raisonné des Sciences, des Arts et des Métiers, Tome 3 CH=CONS, Paris, 1753 p. 102 [https://books.google.com/books?id=zkkJxqFkC-AC&pg=PA102]</ref>
